Just over 50% of people who live in Itasca County have responded to the Census- it's easy to do. If you live here, you count!
The census is just 10 questions and only takes about 5 minutes to complete. Respond to the Census in one of three ways:
· Online at my2020census.gov
· By phone at 844-330-2020
· By completing the form you received at your residence
They are still looking for census workers, too! https://2020census.gov/en/jobs.html

The Coronavirus continues to impact our communities in many ways. If you need assistance with
food, there are opportunities to get the nutritious food your family needs to stay healthy.
If you have children and were receiving SNAP or MFIP as of March 18, 2020, you will receive an
automatic benefit on your EBT card. If you weren’t receiving SNAP or MFIP but your child was
receiving free or reduced lunch, you can apply (until July 31st) for P-EBT to help buy food for your family:
www.mn.p-ebt.org

shared_text:
Minnesota Department of Education
July 9 at 12:28 PM ·

Thank you to the more than 130,000 families who took the time to complete our Fall Planning Survey. We heard your stories of challenging times and the hardship that distance learning placed on you and your loved ones. We also heard your gratitude for keeping our communities safe and spending more time with families.
Your experiences are invaluable as we plan for the 2020-21 school year during these times of uncertainty. It is our shared goal to lift up our students through education, while keeping them safe. Your voices will undoubtedly help us do that.
You can find the full results of our Fall Planning Survey on our website here: https://education.mn.gov/MDE/dse/health/covid19/publicEng/.
As we look toward the future, please know Minnesota school districts and charter schools are working extremely hard to support our students, families and educators. With your help, we will find innovative solutions to the challenges of our times.

Stage 3- August 10-September 4 will include a new left turn lane and crossover between Hwy 169 and Hwy 65.

Minnesota Department of Education
June 12 at 1:00 PM ·

As educators, we must continue to work hard to ensure all students feel safe, welcome and included in our classrooms and our schools. As Education Commissioner Mary Cathryn Ricker says, “we can’t expect our students to conform to our comfort.”

Today, as we honor Pride Month and remember those lost in the Pulse Nightclub Shooting, we are rededicating ourselves to the continued work of lifting up and supporting our LGBTQ+ students and colleagues.

shared_text:
Nashwauk Ambulance Association
June 1 at 7:07 PM ·

2020!!! It’s been interesting to say the least!! With everything that’s happened, all of the uncertainties and emotional moments this year has brought, we want to thank those of you that have allowed us to be a part of making some great memories during some very unpredictable times. We have such great community support it’s been an honor to give back to some of you!!! We’ve been involved in birthday parades, a wedding parade, sending Mrs. Jill Nelson and Mrs. Denise Clausiu’s kindergarten class to first grade, Mrs LauraLee Raukar and Mr. Michael Sievert’s 6th graders to the high school, and the graduating seniors of 2020 in to the world!!! Thank you all so much!!! With a few of the restrictions lifted, and things picking up for us again, we have decided to make today’s parade for the kids of ISD #319 our last. Hopefully we were able to spread some cheer during the shelter in place order. We loved seeing your smiling faces!!! Thank you again!!! We have an amazing community!!!

post_text:
HELP NEEDED! The Itasca County board recently passed a resolution to initiate a crowdsourcing broadband speed test across the County. We want to help the County get good data because this data will help improve broadband access in our area.

All you need to do is click the link, let the test run, and that's it! Do this at home, at the cabin, and repeat it at different times of the day if you are able. If you are in a location with no broadband service, fill in the address and the map will reflect no service.

Click on the link: https://expressoptimizer.net/public/

St. Louis County recently completed this project and it has resulted in some valuable data. Your cooperation is greatly appreciated and this will hopefully lead to better broadband in the near future. Thank you for your time and cooperation!

ALSO, PLEASE SHARE! THANKS!

post_text: Governor Tim Walz announced yesterday that Minnesota schools will continue distance learning through the remainder of the school year. This step was taken as part of a plan to slow the spread of COVID-19 and limit the impact on our healthcare system. We know this has been tough and we will continue to partner with families to support them and their children. Food drops and childcare for workers connected to the COVID response will continue through the rest of the school year. We also want to hear how we are doing. Please click here to tell us: https://my.thoughtexchange.com/984872165

North Star Credit Union
April 20 at 8:17 AM ·

Students at participating schools have an opportunity to earn $25 just by bringing in their grades and a deposit into their accounts.

For every A you get 3 tickets
For every B you get 2 tickets
For every C you get 1 ticket

Deadline is May 1, 2020

This program is to teach students the importance of working hard in school and saving money.

Please have the student tell us the grades by phone or in the vehicle during the transaction. To use our online services for remote deposit without leaving home, visit northstarcreditunion.org.

If you are not a member and want to join, we would be happy to have you save with us.

North Star Credit Union is federally insured by NCUA.

post_text: Remembering a month ago when we were together, and had so much to celebrate. Stay strong and stay healthy, Spartans!
shared_text:
Chloe Morgan Williams
March 13 at 11:48 AM ·

WE ARE THE SPARTANS AND WE COULDN’T BE PROUDER!!!

Boys, we are all so very proud of you. You guys play with your whole heart in every game. You have grown so so much. It has been so much fun watching you play. The memories made and the bonds you have built growing up and playing together will never be replaced. To persevere and persist to keep getting better really shows great character and watching you guys grow and develop into something so extravagant is breathtaking and we all stand proud for you guys. You have given Nashwauk something that we’ve been waiting years for; small towns can make dreams come true too. Thank you for giving our community a good run at the taste of what it feels like to work hard and earn something amazing. We love you!

Seniors, although this was your last run you fall nothing short of amazing. You are huge role models to your community, younger class men, and teammates. You have so much to be proud of you have accomplished so so much though your Journey ￼in basketball. So congratulations on ￼ accomplishing your endeavors. We love you so so much!

post_text:
Happy long weekend Keewatin Elementary Spartan families!
Tuesday, April 14th begins our third week of distance learning.
Thank you so much to our families who are connecting with our teachers, we miss you, and it brightens our day to hear your voices and see your faces. We’re so thankful to be part of such a tightly knit and resilient school community.
Tuesday, April 14th: 9am student learning bundles available for pickup at the elementary school, bus routes will go out in the afternoon. Remember to put out your boxes/bins/ or buckets labeled with your child(ren)'s names!
Starting on Tuesday, April 14th, turn in your child(ren)’s school work online via email, google classroom, or other electronic method. We will no longer collect any student papers or homework on paper from our families.
Have a good long weekend Spartan families,
Stay warm, wash your hands, and stay connected!

post_text:
A few updates for district parents:
1. Beginning Monday, March 30th, students will resume learning at home. The Governor closed schools so we could prepare for a period of Distance Learning, which will start Monday, March 30th. During this time, your student will be learning at home. Expect a call from your student's principal or counselor in the two days explaining what this will look like for your student.
2. We've served over 700 meals at our drop locations in 5 days and want to make sure we are hitting everyone. If your student isn't getting meals, please call your building office at 218-885-1280 and let them know what you need.
3. Check out the links under the COVID-19 menu item at the top of our district website at www.isd319.org for more information about distance learning, food, or childcare.

As was stated in a message earlier in the day, school Minnesota school districts and charter schools will be closed Wednesday, March 18th through Friday, March 27th.

Part of Governor Walz’s plan is that school districts provide childcare to children 12 years or younger who are enrolled in our schools, and are the children of emergency and healthcare workers critical to the COVID-19 response.

If you are a healthcare or emergency worker and will need childcare from the school during the upcoming school closure, please visit the following link:

http://www.tinyurl.com/IASCcare

School district employees will review the childcare needs and communicate the details of the arrangements as soon as we are able.

Thank you for your patience as this situation continues to unfold.

shared_text:
Greenway High School
March 3 at 7:00 PM ·

This Saturday the local FFA Chapters will be putting on a Knockout Hunger Itasca County Event! We have raised over $10,000 to put this event on and are so excited about what it could bring for the community!

The day will start with a panel talking about the hunger issue in Itasca County at 11am. A meal will follow the panel with a meal packaging event starting around 1pm. The event will be taking place right here at Greenway High School in the gym and multipurpose room! We will be packaging a tomato basil hotdish and an oatmeal that will be packaged and given to area food shelves.

This is a great opportunity for students to get some community involvement and volunteer hours. It will also be an awesome time for families to get together and help out the community! If you have a sports team or youth group, it would be an awesome time for some team bonding!

If you are interested in coming to the event check out more information on Greenway FFA's Facebook page or send me an email! There is a link below to the google form to RSVP! https://forms.gle/2y2GL5aHb9zGSfWG7
